^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Okay, this is a hand for demonstrating the law of total tricks. First, let's talk about my 2C bid. If Patti were not a passed hand, I should consider reopening with a double, because it is possible Patti has a hand with spades and cannot bid and I need to protect, in case she has that hand. Since an immediate double by her is negative. Whenever the bidding goes 1x-1 or 2y-p-p, if you are short in y (the overcalled suit), you should strongly consider reopening with a double.|
PG| ***** 46 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|In this case, I am short in spades. However, since Patti was a passed hand originally, it is unlikely we want to penalize 1S, so I decided to just bid my 2nd suit..Now, about sandy's double. That could be takeout. Her shortness in clubs is an asset, and her length in hearts means dee is probably short. It is possible dee has diamonds, so if you want to play that as takeout, that is fine. |
PG| ***** 47 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|My usual rule is that, a double is takeout if 2 specific conditions are met:
1) partner has not bid anything other than pass, that condition was met here;
2) there are at least 2 unbid suits remaining, that condition was not met.
But, many people would take sandy's double as takeout and, dee can work it out since she is long in clubs, so, therefore, it could not be a penalty double.|
PG| ***** 48 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|But playing with my regular partners, I would take it as showing clubs. But that is up to partnership agreement. Now, let's see about Patti. The first pass is ok, although tactically, she might want to bid 3C because she is pretty sure they have a spade fit. I have shown 2 suits, so, although it is possible I have 3 spades, it is more likely I only have 1 or 2. So, although pass is ok, I think 3C is a better choice.|
PG| ***** 49 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Certainly, once it goes 2S-p-p she should bid 3C. Remember to use the law of total tricks to determine how high to bid and the law has two components:
1. the first component is, with a 9 card fit, bid 3 right away. The law is better for determining how high to bid in competitive auctions;
2. the 2nd component is, if they are at the 2 level, you should bid to the 3 level even with only an 8 card fit. |
PG| ***** 50 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Basically, with an 8 card fit, you should not let them play at the 2 level.|
