NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Well, that's exactly my point. if you open 2C, you need to plan out your next bid.|
PG| ***** 137 ***** |


AT|
robzim: Over your 2 hearts -- I can see :  (a) I miscounted losers and (b) I had no rebid.|
PG| ***** 138 ***** |


cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|But before you open 2C, you must know what you are going to bid over the likely 2D response. I think you have 2 choices on this hand. 1C is one choice. The other choice is 2N. I think 1C is slightly better. 2C is not really viable because you have no good rebid over whatever I bid.|
PG| ***** 139 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Now, let me discuss the 2 alternative response structures to 2C. One is what Roberta plays, 2D promises at least one A or K, and 2H denies an A or K. The other is what is known as 2nd negative. In 2nd negative, 2D can be made with a bust hand and then over a suit bid by Roberta, a bid of your cheapest minor shows a bust hand.|
PG| ***** 140 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|So, with a bust hand, if it goes 2C-2D-2H/2S a bid of 3C by the 2D responder is how you show a bust.|
PG| ***** 141 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|The important cards for responder when partner opens 2C are Aces and Kings. Therefore, a bust is defined as any hand which lacks an Ace or King. Some people use point count, but most experts are more interested in aces and kings. So, even if you have 6 or 7 points, but lack Aces and Kings, you should consider  your hand a "bust" (and that almost never happens in real life). Now, if partner rebids 2N, showing 23-24, of course you should raise to 3 with enough points, even lacking an ace or king. |
PG| ***** 142 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|But, in terms of going to slam, lack of Aces and Kings is a big minus regardless of how many HCP responder has. I used to prefer the 2H bust hand, but I have now gone over to the 2nd negative approach because on many 2C openers, partner bids 2N anyway and on most others they bid 2H or 2S. In this hand, once Roberta bids 2N I have a perfect garbage Stayman. So, whatever Roberta bids over 3C I was intending to pass. But since she was nice enough to pass dee's double, I got to play 3D :).|
PG| ***** 143 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|One more comment on responses to 2C. Assuming you don't play 2H bust, a 2H or 2S response to 2C promises a 5+ card suit with 2 of the top 3 or 3 of the top 5 honors. If you do play 2H as bust, then some play a 2N bid by responder shows hearts. 
|
